America's pastime. Pork hot dogs here are so boring: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_league_baseball Pork chop entrees here are so amazing: Brined with balsamic for two days and served atop Brussels sprouts and pine nuts. Rarely order pork. Never happier with the decision. Enjoyed after a starter of smoked trout deviled eggs with fried garlic and lemon complements. Indulgent and delicious. Somehow saved room for a few bites of butterscotch pudding topped with pecan brittle. Somehow had the discipline not to eat the whole thing. Polished interior and staff reinforced the confident approach to food and service. Great spot for a date or catching up with a close friend. You could spend upwards of $100 to go to the baseball game with no certainty of the outcome. Or for about $40 (no drinks) you can be very certain of four very deserved stars.

I crave the food at Blue Plate about once or twice a month. The food is consistently delicious! Try the deviled eggs, meatloaf and coconut cream pie. I hope you enjoy it as much as I do!

Can't say I was much of a fan at Blue Plate. It was my 4th anniversary with my girlfriend and we decided to try something new rather than browse around aimlessly for our next 'cheap food fix'. I happened to stumble upon Blue Plate many times as I work around the area and 'American' food was a foreign realm to us. The service was great, but the food wasn't really up my alley. The starters were decent, but wish there was a bit more of lamb in the Gnocchi And Slow-cooked Lamb. There was also a plate with pork belly, but I can't remember the name of it. The focaccia bread that was given was really nice. Only problem was the amount of salt put into it which ruined what would have been a real treat. As for our entrees, we had the Fried Chicken and Mac and Cheese. The Fried Chicken was salty to the point where I couldn't stomach it. This came to me as a surprise because there wasn't that much breading to it. The Mac and Cheese tasted great, but I wish it wasn't too grain-y (it might have been the roux or something). The atmosphere was alright. My girlfriend and I decided to get a seat in the middle room which in hindsight was a big mistake. The lighting in the middle of the room was too bright for my taste and the candle that was on the middle of the table was electric. Some tea lights would have been great as well as dimming the lights a bit. Perhaps it was just me wanting to have a more intimate feel for a special day. I really kicked myself for not sitting in the front of the restaurant with the dim lighting and kitchen staff right there. Overall, Blue Plate was a nice experience, but I can't say I'll be coming back anytime soon.

I actually really like this place and end up going here once a year with work colleagues. It's a bit pricier than your normal eat-out, but for special occasion(ish), it's a good bet. I love the house-turned-restaurant atmosphere, and the servers are all nice, there's a good (if not a bit more marked up than necessary) wine list, etc. So why the three stars: I am ALWAYS disappointed by their vegetarian entree. Always. The menu rotates some, so the entree is never the same vegetarian entree (and there is only ONE vegetarian entree, mind you). So I was hopeful this last round that the vegetarian entree would step it up to match what looks like other people's very fine meaty-meat entrees. It was beautifully presented, as is all the food, but was basically a spinachy-veggie-loaf, which could have been interesting, but was so lacking in flavor or spicing that I had to add salt and a sauce from someone else's plate to make it more than just a mouth-full-of-spinach. I know that Yelp says vegetarians go nuts for this place, but it must be the mac-n-cheese side (which truly is divine) that gets them there, because there is only ever one veggie-friendly entree and it just disappoints. Meat-eaters can eat here with glee, but I'm warning vegetarians out there: it can be hit and miss for you (including many of the side "salads" that are infused with meats, etc.)

Still and sparkling water was on the house along with AMAZINGGGG focaccia bread (we got a refill). I would eat loaves of this every day if I could. Ordered: gnocchi and slow-cooked lamb (really good appetizer with melt in your mouth gnocchi), and we also got the pan-seared diver scallops that were really good. The meatloaf was really good and stays on the menu along with the fried chicken (good but a bit on the salty and dry side) and the drunk spanish goat cheese macaroni (worth getting for the table). The service is good and the place is very homey. We finished off the meal with pie (huge slice), an assortment of desserts, and an affagato. Reservations weren't too hard to get and a group up to 6 can be easily seated at the restaurant.

Om nom nom. I've lived in the Mission my entire life and I'm finally eating more around the area... and I can finally say proudly that I live in the mission! Minus the stray bullets flying pass me and the hipsters on every corner. Made reservations here for a Friday night at 630. Got here and the place is TINY. If you don't have reservations, I would definitely come early then. Anyway, got seated. Shared the grilled kale and pomegranate chopped salad, mac and cheese, fried chicken, and the meatloaf. The kale salad was good. I love kale in general... so you have to intentionally ruin kale to make me hate it. But they also had bacon and bacon makes everything good! The pomegranate was definitely a nice twist. Everything blended well. The mac and cheese came next and the waiter put it down and said "careful it's hot." Now, usually people say that but it's like WARM at most. The 5 year old inside me just had to touch it... and that b*tch was hot! Definitely don't touch that bowl! Anyway, the mac and cheese was piping hot (of course). Cheese nice and stringy. If it didn't say in the menu that it was goat cheese, I wouldn't even be able to tell. The goat cheese wasn't overpowering and the entire dish was DELICIOUS! The meatloaf was pretty good too. I'm not usually a big meatloaf fan... you have to make some bombass meatloaf to blow me away. Now this wasn't one that rocked my world but the meatloaf was definitely tasty and was moist. Mash potatoes were nice and creamy. Nice to eat a spoonful of potatoes with the meatloaf... mmm! The fried chicken was really good. Is it sad to say that I liked the pickled vegetables just as much? lol. But the chicken was crunchy, moist, and flavorful. The jalepeno buttermilk dressing that came with it was alright... it was missing something though. I may have just really craved ranch sauce that night... but I guess that would have overpowered the chicken. Oh well! Meal overall was really good. Prices are reasonable and portions are good too. Service we got was good too. Definitely would recommend to others to try!

Blue Plate is nice, but for the price, I expect a little more. Service was attentive, but a little awkward. Good appetizers, though fairly small as is typical at finer dining establishments (oh well) - the tuna tartare was purportedly amazing, but I never got any; our beet salad was fine, just not special. Entrees were the main issues. I thought the meatloaf was too insubstantial, alongside a huge, gooey (though creamy) mass of mashed potatoes, and a few crisp green beans that had no real flavor. The crab special was odd but ok--I'm not sure what the overall effect was supposed to be, but it was definitely unusual. Kind of liked it, not sure why. The mac and cheese side was typical--it had no topping of breadcrumbs or some such that differentiates the good m&c from the addictive.. Two of the three desserts were excellent, the affogato was rad (great espresso, Illy, I think) and the butterscotch pudding, though oversalted, was very tasty. Actually, my bf said that everything was oversalted, which may be true. The main reason we came was the key lime pie, but sadly, the recipe had been altered and it was a bit too sweet. $200 with wine (a nice if unexciting Prosecco) for four is not too bad, but again, except for dessert, this was not a memorable meal.

    Seated via Yelp Reservations

    Can't say I was much of a fan at Blue Plate. It was my 4th anniversary with my girlfriend and we decided to try something new rather than browse around aimlessly for our next 'cheap food fix'.  I happened to stumble upon Blue Plate many times as I work around the area and 'American' food was a foreign realm to us. The service was great, but the food wasn't really up my alley.

    The starters were decent, but wish there was a bit more of lamb in the Gnocchi And Slow-cooked Lamb. There was also a plate with pork belly, but I can't remember the name of it. The focaccia bread that was given was really nice. Only problem was the amount of salt put into it which ruined what would have been a real treat.

    As for our entrees, we had the Fried Chicken and Mac and Cheese. The Fried Chicken was salty to the point where I couldn't stomach it. This came to me as a surprise because there wasn't that much breading to it. The Mac and Cheese tasted great, but I wish it wasn't too grain-y (it might have been the roux or something).

    The atmosphere was alright. My girlfriend and I decided to get a seat in the middle room which in hindsight was a big mistake. The lighting in the middle of the room was too bright for my taste and the candle that was on the middle of the table was electric. Some tea lights would have been great as well as dimming the lights a bit. Perhaps it was just me wanting to have a more intimate feel for a special day. I really kicked myself for not sitting in the front of the restaurant with the dim lighting and kitchen staff right there.

    Overall, Blue Plate was a nice experience, but I can't say I'll be coming back anytime soon.

    I actually really like this place and end up going here once a year with work colleagues.  It's a bit pricier than your normal eat-out, but for special occasion(ish), it's a good bet.  I love the house-turned-restaurant atmosphere, and the servers are all nice, there's a good (if not a bit more marked up than necessary) wine list, etc.  So why the three stars: I am ALWAYS disappointed by their vegetarian entree.  Always.  The menu rotates some, so the entree is never the same vegetarian entree (and there is only ONE vegetarian entree, mind you).  So I was hopeful this last round that the vegetarian entree would step it up to match what looks like other people's very fine meaty-meat entrees.  It was beautifully presented, as is all the food, but was basically a spinachy-veggie-loaf, which could have been interesting, but was so lacking in flavor or spicing that I had to add salt and a sauce from someone else's plate to make it more than just a  mouth-full-of-spinach.  

    I know that Yelp says vegetarians go nuts for this place, but it must be the mac-n-cheese side (which truly is divine) that gets them there, because there is only ever one veggie-friendly entree and it just disappoints.  

    Meat-eaters can eat here with glee, but I'm warning vegetarians out there: it can be hit and miss for you (including many of the side "salads" that are infused with meats, etc.)

The tables were very closet together & If anything will make think twice about coming back, this element of the experience would. I knocked it down from four to three stars for this reason.

    2/6/2015

    Blue Plate is nice, but for the price, I expect a little more.

    Service was attentive, but a little awkward. Good appetizers, though fairly small as is typical at finer dining establishments (oh well) - the tuna tartare was purportedly amazing, but I never got any; our beet salad was fine, just not special.

    Entrees were the main issues. I thought the meatloaf was too insubstantial, alongside a huge, gooey (though creamy) mass of mashed potatoes, and a few crisp green beans that had no real flavor.  The crab special was odd but ok--I'm not sure what the overall effect was supposed to be, but it was definitely unusual.  Kind of liked it, not sure why. The mac and cheese side was typical--it had no topping of breadcrumbs or some such that differentiates the good m&c from the addictive..

    Two of the three desserts were excellent, the affogato was rad (great espresso, Illy, I think) and the butterscotch pudding, though oversalted, was very tasty. Actually, my bf said that everything was oversalted, which may be true.

    The main reason we came was the key lime pie, but sadly, the recipe had been altered and it was a bit too sweet.

    $200 with wine (a nice if unexciting Prosecco) for four is not too bad, but again, except for dessert, this was not a memorable meal.
